{{Infobox Museum |name = Australian Computer Museum Society Inc |established = 1994 |dissolved = |location = [[Sydney]], [[Australia]] |type = [[Computer museum]] |visitors = unknown |president = John Deane |website = [http://www.acms.org.au/ www.acms.org.au] }}
The '''Australian Computer Museum Society Inc''', (ACMS) is a society dedicated to the preservation of the history of computing in [[Australia]], including software, hardware, operating systems and literature.<ref>{{cite news |title=Crash goes that computer museum |url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/06/22/1087844937265.html |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=23 June 2004 |accessdate=7 December 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Computer heritage faces storage crisis |url=http://www.news.com.au/technology/retro-technology-faces-the-tip/story-e6frfro0-1111116208520 |work=[[News.com.au]] |date=1 May 2008 |accessdate=7 December 2012 }}</ref> ACMS was registered and is a charitable institution which relies on memberships and donations to operate. Established in 1994,<ref>{{cite news |title=Nothing lasts forever, not even modern media |url=http://www.abc.net.au/http/sfist/archivs.htm |work=[[The Australian]] |date=1 November 1994 |accessdate=7 December 2012 }}</ref> their members have since amassed a large number of unique devices designed and built by Australians.
